# 28. Processing / Progress Rules

Any operation that processes data — load, create, update, delete, import, export
— MUST give the user visual processing feedback and must prevent double submit.

Rules:

- Action buttons that trigger async work MUST set `IsAsync="true"` so the button
  shows its built-in spinner and is disabled while running.
- For longer operations with a known percentage (import/export/batch), use the
  `<Progress>` component bound to a value.
- For indeterminate longer operations, show a full overlay `<Spinner>` with a
  message and disable the surrounding form.
- After completion, show a success `Toast` and refresh the affected data.
- Guard against re-entry with a `_processing` flag (or rely on `IsAsync`).

Async button (auto spinner + disabled while running):

```razor
<Button Text="Tạo mới" Icon="fa-solid fa-plus" Color="Color.Success"
        IsAsync="true" OnClick="CreateAsync" />
```

Determinate progress (e.g. import):

```razor
@if (_processing)
{
    <Progress Value="_progress" IsShowValue="true" Color="Color.Primary" />
}
```

```csharp
private bool _processing;
private double _progress;

private async Task ImportAsync()
{
    _processing = true;
    _progress = 0;
    try
    {
        // Report progress as each chunk completes
        await DataService.ImportAsync(_file, p =>
        {
            _progress = p;
            InvokeAsync(StateHasChanged);
        });
        await ToastService.Success("Hoàn tất", "Đã nhập dữ liệu.");
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        await SwalService.Show(new SwalOption
        {
            Category = SwalCategory.Error,
            Title = "Nhập dữ liệu thất bại",
            Content = ex.Message
        });
    }
    finally
    {
        _processing = false;
    }
}
```

Do not:

- Fire create/update/delete without disabling the trigger.
- Leave the user without feedback during a long-running task.

